Title:
LainAmsiOpenSession — Custom AMSI bypass by patching AmsiOpenSession in amsi.dll

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This repository provides a PowerShell-based AMSI bypass that patches the `AmsiOpenSession` function inside `amsi.dll` in-memory.  
- The goal is to prevent or disrupt AMSI session initialization so subsequent script/content scanning is impaired, enabling execution of PowerShell payloads that would otherwise be inspected.  
- It is derived from/related to prior public techniques (Sam Rothlisberger’s AMSI bypass) and takes inspiration from “Nuke-Amsi,” indicating a focus on direct function patching rather than higher-level flag toggles.  
- The technique centers on runtime modification of a Windows security component (AMSI) via API resolution and memory patching.  
- It is primarily useful for red team operators and pentesters performing Windows post-exploitation where AMSI blocks offensive PowerShell.  
- It’s interesting because it targets a less commonly patched AMSI function (`AmsiOpenSession`) and demonstrates a practical in-process patching approach.

Technical Focus:
- AMSI internals (`amsi.dll`) and session lifecycle (`AmsiOpenSession`)
- In-memory function patching / byte patching
- PowerShell-based native API invocation (P/Invoke / reflection patterns)
- Runtime DLL function resolution (e.g., `GetProcAddress`-style logic)
- Memory protection changes (e.g., `VirtualProtect`) for patching

Use Cases:
- Bypassing AMSI scanning during PowerShell-based post-exploitation
- Running known-signature PowerShell tooling in constrained/monitored environments
- Red team tradecraft experimentation with alternative AMSI patch points
- Testing blue-team detections for in-memory tampering of `amsi.dll`

Keywords:
AMSI, amsi.dll, AmsiOpenSession, PowerShell, in-memory patching, function patch, VirtualProtect, GetProcAddress, runtime hooking, EDR evasion, script scanning, Windows internals, post-exploitation, offensive PowerShell, Nuke-Amsi, Sam Rothlisberger, memory protection, API patching